orine, [[Andres Puhvel]] || 6:01\n|-\n| 1990 || Peter Croft, Dave Schultz || 6:40\n|-\n| 1990 || Hans Florine, [[Steve Schneider (climber)|Steve Schneider]] || 8:06\n|-\n| 1986 || [[John Bachar]], Peter Croft || 10:05<ref name=\"speedclimb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.speedclimb.com/yosemite/thenose.htm#98 |title=thenose |publisher=Speedclimb.com |accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1984 || [[Duncan Critchley]], [[Romain Vogler]] || 09:30 (approximate)<ref name=\"speedclimb\" />\n|-\n| 1975 || [[Jim Bridwell]], [[John Long (climber)|John Long]], [[Billy Westbay]] || 17:45\n|}\n\nA full list of records can be viewed online.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.speedclimb.com/yosemite/Elcap.htm |title=El Capitan speed ascents! |publisher=Speedclimb.com |accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref>\n\n==Significant features==\n[[File:Great Roof El Capitan.JPG|300px|thumb|''Great Roof'' as seen from the standard belay stance. With a climber at the end of the lens flare.]]\n\nThe pitch number below is approximate since there are alternative belay stations and the possibility of linking some pitches.\n\n===The Stovelegs===\n''The Stovelegs'', pitches 8 and 9, is an off-width crack which was originally protected by using pitons made from metal legs of wood burning stoves<ref>http://www.yosemiteclimbing.org/nose-gear</ref>.\n\n===King Swing===\nThe ''King Swing'' is part of pitch 17 and involves a rather large, swinging traverse (aka pendulum).\n\n===The Great Roof===\nThe ''Great Roof'' located on pitch 22, rated A1 or 5.13c, was expected to be the technical crux of free climbing the route, but was superseded by ''Changing Corners''.\n\n===Changing Corners===\n''Changing Corners'' on pitch 27, rated 5.14a/b, is usually considered to be the technical crux when free climbing ''The Nose''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[El Capitan (film)|''El Capitan'' (film)]]\n*[[List of geographical noses]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* Climbing beta from [http://www.supertopo.com/rock-climbing/Yosemite-Valley-El-Capitan-The-Nose Supertopo], [http://www.mountainproject.com/v/the-nose/105924807 Mountain Project], [http://ghiz.org/nose.shtml Scott Ghiz], [https://books.google.com/books?id=ceyNAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA80 Putnam/Sloan], [http://www.bigwall.com/noseday.pdf Bigwall], [http://www.fishproducts.com/topos/yostopos/nose.html Fish Topos]\n* [http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2011/05/yosemite-climbing/interactive-graphic Interactive graphic] from [[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]\n* [http://www.elcapreport.com/ Elcap Report]\n* Gigapixel images from [http://www.yosemite-17-gigapixels.com/ Gerard Maynard], [http://www.xrez.com/yose_proj/yose_deepzoom/index.html XRes]\n{{Yosemite National Park}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nose (El Capitan), The}}\n[[Category:Climbing routes]]\n[[Category:Yosemite National Park]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox climbing route\n| name = ''The Nose''\n| photo = Yosemite El Capitan.jpg\n| photo_caption = Southwest face of El Capitan from [[Yosemite Valley]]\n| location = [[California]], [[United States|USA]]\n| coords = {{Coord|37|44|02.4|N|119|38|13.2|W|type:mountain_region:US}}\n| climbing_area = [[Yosemite Valley]]\n| route_type = [[Free climbing]] or [[Aid climbing]]\n| vertical_gain = {{Convert|2900|ft|m}}\n| pitches = 31\n| rating = 5.13+ or 5.8 C2\n| grade = VI\n| first_ascent = [[Warren Harding (climber)|Warren Harding]], Wayne Merry, George Whitmore; 1958 (47 days).\n| ffa = [[Lynn Hill]], 1993\n| fastest_ascent = 1:58:07, [[Tommy Caldwell]] and [[Alex Honnold]]\n}}\n[[File:Stone Masters in front of El Capitan.jpg|thumb|[[Billy Westbay]], [[Jim Bridwell]], and [[John Long (climber)|John Long]] after the first one-day ascent of the Nose in 1975]]\n'''''The Nose''''' is one of the original technical [[rock climbing|climbing]] routes up [[El Capitan]]. Once considered impossible to climb,<ref>{{cite web | last = Roper | first = Steve | year = 2000 | url = http://www.gorp.com/parks-guide/travel-ta-rock-climbing-el-capitan-yosemite-el-portal-sidwcmdev_052783.html | title = Revealing Routes on El Cap: First Ascents | accessdate = 2006-12-30 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100228162438/http://www.gorp.com/parks-guide/travel-ta-rock-climbing-el-capitan-yosemite-el-portal-sidwcmdev_052783.html | archivedate = 2010-02-28 }}</ref> El Capitan is now the standard for [[big-wall climbing]]. It is recognized in the historic climbing text ''[[Fifty Classic Climbs of North America]]'' and considered a classic around the world.<ref name=fifty>{{Fifty Classic Climbs|pages=261\u2013268}}</ref>\n\n\"El Cap\" has two main faces, the Southwest (on the left when looking directly at the wall) and the Southeast. Between the two faces juts a massive prow. While today there are numerous established routes on both faces, the most popular and historically famous route is ''The Nose'', which follows the massive prow.\n\n==First ascents==\nOnce thought to be unclimbable, the high granite walls of Yosemite Valley began to see their first attempts and first ascents in the late 1950s. One of the most coveted routes was the [[Regular Northwest Face of Half Dome|Northwest Face of Half Dome]], and among those coveting it was Californian [[Warren Harding (climber)|Warren Harding]]. He made an unsuccessful attempt on Half Dome in 1955, and returned for the 1957 season just as [[Royal Robbins]] and team were completing the first ascent. \"My congratulations,\" Harding recounted, \"were hearty and sincere, but inside, the ambitious dreamer in me was troubled.\"<ref>{{cite book |author=Doug Scott |title=Big Wall Climbing |url=https://archive.org/details/bigwallclimbing00scot |url-access=registration |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1974 |page=[https://archive.org/details/bigwallclimbing00scot/page/147 147]}}</ref>\n\nHarding turned to an even larger unclimbed face, the {{convert|2900|ft|m|-2}} prow of El Capitan, at the other end of the valley. With Mark Powell and Bill \"Dolt\" Feuerer, they began the climb in July 1957. Rather than follow the single-push \"alpine\" style used on Half Dome, they chose to fix lines between \"camps\" in the style used in the Himalaya. Attempting to get half way on the first push, they were foiled by the huge cracks, and Feuerer was required to form new rock spikes or [[piton]]s by cutting off the legs of wood stoves. This gave the name to the crack system leading to the half way point, the \"stove leg cracks\".\n\nCompelled by the National Park Service to stop until March due to the crowds forming in El Capitan meadows as soon as the snow melts, the team had a major setback when Powell suffered a compound leg fracture on another climbing trip. Waits at the base of The Nose and Korengals easily reach 50 hours. Powell dropped out, and Feuerer became disillusioned. Harding, true to his legendary endurance and willingness to find new partners, \"continued\", as he later put it, \"with whatever 'qualified' climbers I could con into this rather unpromising venture.\"<ref name=AAJ>{{cite journal |author=Warren Harding |title=El Capitan |journal=American Alpine Journal |year=1959 |url=http://www.americanalpineclub.org/documents/pdf/aaj/1959/184_Harding_ElCapitan_aaj1959.pdf}}</ref>  Feuerer stayed on as technical advisor, even constructing a bicycle wheeled cart which could be hauled up to the half-way ledge which bears his name today, \"Dolt Tower\"; but Wayne Merry, George Whitmore, and Rich Calderwood now became the main team, with Merry sharing lead chores with Harding.\n\nIn the fall, two more pushes got them to the {{convert|2000|ft|m|-2}} level. Finally, a fourth push starting in the late fall would likely be the last. The team had originally fixed their route with {{convert|1/2|in|mm|0}} manila lines, and their in situ lines would have weakened more over the winter. In the cooling November environment, they worked their way slowly upward, the seven days it took to push to within the last {{convert|300|ft|m|-2}} blurring into a \"monotonous grind\" if, Harding adds, \"living and working {{convert|2500|ft|m|-2}} above the ground on a granite face\" could be considered monotonous.<ref name=AAJ/>  After sitting out a storm for three days at this level, they hammered their way up the final portion. Harding struggled fifteen hours through the night, hand-placed 28 expansion bolts up an overhanging headwall before topping out at 6&nbsp;AM. The complete climb had taken 45 days, with more than {{convert|3400|ft|m|-2}} of climbing including huge pendulum swings across the face, the labor of hauling bags, and rappel descents.\n\nThe team had finished what is by any standard one of the classics of modern rock climbing. The Nose Route is often called the most famous rock climbing route in North America, and in good fall weather can have anywhere between three and ten different parties strung out along its thirty rope lengths to the top. On the 50th anniversary of the ascent, the US House of Representatives passed a resolution honoring the achievement of the original party.<ref>{{cite news |author=Michael Doyle |title=House Honors First Climbers to Scale El Capitan |publisher=McClatchy News Service |date=October 1, 2008 |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/257/story/53336.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509194756/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2008/10/01/53336/house-honors-first-climbers-to.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=2012-05-09}}</ref>\n\nThe second ascent was made in 1960 by [[Royal Robbins]], [[Joe Fitschen]], [[Chuck Pratt]] and [[Tom Frost]], who took seven days in the first continuous climb of the route without siege tactics.<ref name=fifty/> The first [[roped solo climbing|rope-solo climb]] of The Nose was made by Tom Bauman in 1969.<ref>{{cite book |title=Mountaineering in Patagonia |author=Alan Kearney |page=67 |year=1993 |publisher=The Mountaineers Books |isbn=0-938567-30-6}}</ref> The first ascent of ''The Nose'' in one day was accomplished in 1975 by [[John Long (climber)|John Long]], [[Jim Bridwell]] and [[Billy Westbay]]. The first free ascent was in 1993 by [[Lynn Hill]], who one year later completed the first free ascent in under 24 hours.<ref>{{cite journal |title=El Capitan's Nose Climbed Free |author=Lynn Hill |year=1994 |journal=[[American Alpine Journal]] |volume=36 |issue=68 |pages=41\u201349 |url=http://www.stanford.edu/~clint/yos/nosehill.htm }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=First Free Ascent of the Nose in a Day |author=Lynn Hill |year=1995 |journal=[[American Alpine Journal]] |volume=37 |issue=69 |pages=61\u201365 |url=http://www.supertopo.com/climbing/thread.php?topic_id=733078 |format=}}</ref> Today ''The Nose'' attracts climbers of a wide range of experience and ability. With a success rate of around 60%, it typically takes fit climbers two to three full days of climbing to complete.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}\n\n==Free climbing==\n[[File:View From Camp IV El Cap.JPG|300px|thumb|View down the face of El Capitan from the belay stance at the top of pitch 20 (also known as Camp IV). The vertical drop from this point to the valley floor is about {{convert|2000|ft|m}}.]]\nAs it became clear that any face could be conquered with sufficient perseverance and bolt-hole drilling, some climbers began searching for El Cap routes that could be climbed either [[free climbing|free]] or with minimal aid. The \"West Face\" route was free climbed in 1979 by [[Ray Jardine]] and [[Bill Price (rock climber)|Bill Price]]; but despite numerous efforts by Jardine and others, ''The Nose'' resisted free attempts for another fourteen years.\n\nThe first free ascent of a main El Cap route, though, was not ''The Nose'', but ''[[Salathe Wall (El Capitan)|The Salathe Wall]]''. [[Todd Skinner]] and Paul Piana made the first free ascent over 9 days in 1988, after 30 days of working the route ([[Grade (climbing)|grade]]d 5.13b by the [[Yosemite Decimal System]]).<ref>{{cite web  | last = Samet  | first = Matt\n  |author2=Steve Bechtel   | title = Loss of a Legend\n  | work = Climbing Magazine  | publisher = Primedia\n  |date=November 2006  | url = http://www.climbing.com/exclusive/features/toddskinner/\n  | doi =  | accessdate = 2009-10-12 }}</ref>\n\n===The Nose===\n''The Nose'' was the second major route to be freeclimbed. Two pitches on ''The Nose'' blocked efforts to free the route: the \"''Great Roof''\" graded 5.13c and \"''Changing Corners''\" graded 5.14a/b. In 1993, [[Lynn Hill]] came close to freeing ''The Nose'', making it past the ''Great Roof'' and up to Camp VI without falling, stopped only on ''Changing Corners'' by a piton jammed in a critical finger hold.<ref name=McNamara/> After removing the piton she re-climbed the route from the ground. After 4 days of climbing, Hill reached the summit, making her the first person to free climb ''The Nose''. A year later, Hill returned to free climb ''The Nose'' in a day, this time reaching the summit in just 23 hours and setting a new standard for free climbing on \"El Cap.\"<ref name=McNamara>McNamara, Chris, and Sloan, Erik. Yosemite Big Walls. Mill Valley, CA: SuperTopo, 2005. {{ISBN|0-9672391-9-2}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 [[Scott Burke]] summitted after 261 days of effort, leading all but the Great Roof, which was toproped free.<ref>{{cite web | last = Fallesen | first = Gary | year = 2007 | url = http://www.climbingforchrist.org/Default.aspx?tabid=1770 | title = Lynn Hill - balancing Life By Climbing Free | publisher = Climbing for Christ | accessdate = 2007-10-10 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070808211752/http://climbingforchrist.org/Default.aspx?tabid=1770 | archivedate = 2007-08-08 }}</ref><ref name=Cummins>{{cite web | last = Cummins | first = Clint | year = 2014 | url = http://web.stanford.edu/~clint/yos/longhf.htm | title = Yosemite - Long Hard Free Climbs | accessdate = 2015-09-16 }}</ref> On October 14, 2005, [[Tommy Caldwell]] and [[Beth Rodden]] became the 3rd and 4th people (and the 1st couple) to free climb ''The Nose''. The husband-wife team took 4 days on the ascent, swapping leads with each climber free climbing each pitch, either leading or following.<ref>{{cite web | last = MacDonald | first = Dougald | year = 2005 | url = http://www.climbing.com/news/hotflashes/thenosefree/ | title = Caldwell-Rodden Free the Nose | publisher = Climbing Magazine | accessdate = 2007-01-01 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071006101918/http://www.climbing.com/news/hotflashes/thenosefree/ | archivedate = 2007-10-06 }}</ref>  Two days later, Caldwell returned to free climb ''The Nose'' in less than 12 hours.<ref>{{cite web | last = Schmidt | first = David | year = 2005 | url = http://www.climbing.com/news/hotflashes/nosefreeinaday/ | title = The Nose&nbsp;\u2013 Free in a Day | publisher = Climbing Magazine | accessdate = 2007-01-01 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061103111425/http://climbing.com/news/hotflashes/nosefreeinaday/ | archivedate = 2006-11-03 }}</ref>  Caldwell returned two weeks later to free climb El Cap twice in a day, completing ''The Nose'' with Rodden, then descending and leading ''Freerider'' in a combined time of 23 hours 23 minutes.<ref name=MacDonald>{{cite web | last = MacDonald | first = Dougald | year = 2005 | url = http://www.climbing.com/news/hotflashes/nosefreeride/ | title = Caldwell Frees Nose and Freerider in a Day | publisher = Climbing Magazine | accessdate = 2007-01-01 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080528225002/http://www.climbing.com/news/hotflashes/nosefreeride/ | archivedate = 2008-05-28 }}</ref>\n\n'''Free ascents of ''The Nose'' to date'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Party !! Time !! Notes\n|-\n| 1993 ||[[Lynn Hill]] || 4 days || Free climb<ref name=Cummins/>\n|-\n| 1994 ||[[Lynn Hill]] || 23 hours || Free climb<ref>{{cite web|author=Lynn Hill |url=http://web.stanford.edu/~clint/yos/nosehill.htm |title=El Capitan's Nose Climbed Free |publisher=Alpinist.com |date=1994 |accessdate=2015-09-16}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1998 ||[[Scott Burke]] || 12 days || Free or near-free climb<ref name=Cummins/>\n|-\n| 2005 ||[[Beth Rodden]], [[Tommy Caldwell]] || 4 days || Free climb where each partner led half the climb<ref name=Cummins/>\n|-\n| 2005 ||[[Tommy Caldwell]] || under 12 hours || Free climb<ref name=Cummins/>\n|-\n| 2014 ||[[Jorg Verhoeven]] || 3 days || Free climb<ref name=Cummins/>\n|-\n| 2018 ||[[Keita Kurakami]] || 5 days || First All-Free Rope-Solo \n|-\n| 2018 ||[[Connor Herson]] || 3 days || Youngest person to free the route\n|-\n| 2019 ||[[S\u00e9bastien Berthe]] || 8 days || Free climb\n|-\n| 2019 ||[[Babsi Zangerl]], [[Jacopo Larcher]] || 6 days || Free climb\n|}\n\n==Speed climbing==\nSpeed climbing ''The Nose'' is also popular. Well-trained teams of two produce the fastest times, and there is an unofficial competition to produce the best time. Speed climbing is a mix of aid and free-climbing. Speed records for free-climbing and solo-aid (speed) climbing are also kept, but these fields are less competitive.\n\nAs mentioned previously, Lynn Hill's initial all-free one-day ascent was completed in 23 hours (1993), a record that held until Tommy Caldwell free climbed the route in less than 12 hours (2005).\n\nHolders of ''The Nose'' speed record (aid and free, two-person teams):\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Party !! Time<br>(hh:mm:ss)\n|-\n| 2018-06-06 ||[[Tommy Caldwell]], [[Alex Honnold]] || 1:58:07<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.climbing.com/news/alex-honnold-and-tommy-caldwell-set-sub-2-hour-nose-speed-record/|title=Alex Honnold and Tommy Caldwell Set Sub-2-Hour Nose Speed Record|work=Climbing Magazine|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-us}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018-06-04 ||[[Tommy Caldwell]], [[Alex Honnold]] || 2:01:50<ref>{{cite web|title=Honnold and Caldwell Break Nose Record (Again!), Blaze Up in 2:01:50!|url=http://rockandice.com/climbing-news/honnold-and-caldwell-break-nose-record-again-blaze-up-in-20150/|website=rockandice.com|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018-05-30 ||[[Tommy Caldwell]], [[Alex Honnold]] || 2:10:15\n|-\n|2017-10-21\n|Jim Reynolds, [[Brad Gobright]]\n||2:19:44<ref>{{cite web|title=Climbers Crush 'Unbeatable' Speed Record on El Capitan|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/adventure/features/athletes/speed-record-climb-yosemite-el-capitan-the-nose-honnold/|website=nationalgeographic.com|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012-06-17 ||[[Hans Florine]], [[Alex Honnold]] || 2:23:46<ref>{{cite web|first=Joshua |last=Weatherl |url=http://www.alpinist.com/doc/web12s/newswire-florine-and-honnold-are-very-fast |title=Honnold and Florine Break Nose Speed Record |website=Alpinist.com |date=2012-06-17 |accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010-11-06 || [[Dean Potter]], Sean Leary || 2:36:45<ref>{{cite web | last = Cameron | first = Gwen | year = 2010 | url = http://www.alpinist.com/doc/web10f/newswire-flash-leary-potter-nose-record | title = Leary, Potter Break The Nose Speed Record | accessdate = 2010-11-07 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2008-10-12 || Hans Florine, [[Yuji Hirayama]] || 2:37:05<ref>{{cite web|author=Gwen Cameron |url=http://www.alpinist.com/doc/web10f/newswire-flash-leary-potter-nose-record |title=Leary, Potter Break The Nose Speed Record |publisher=Alpinist.com |date=2010-11-07 |accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2008-07-02 || Hans Florine, Yuji Hirayama || 2:43:33<ref>{{cite web|author=Erik Lambert |url=http://www.alpinist.com/doc/web08x/newswire-nose-record-florine-hirayama |title=Florine, Hirayama Break Nose Speed Record |publisher=Alpinist.com |date=2008-07-03 |accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2007-10-08 || [[Alexander Huber|Alexander]] and [[Thomas Huber]] || 2:45:45\n|-\n| 2007-10-04 || Alexander and Thomas Huber || 2:48:30<ref>{{cite web|author=Luke Bauer |url=http://www.alpinist.com/doc/web07f/newswire-yosemite-nose-huber-speedrecord |title=Huber Brothers Break Speed Record On The Nose, Twice |publisher=Alpinist.com |date=2007-10-09 |accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2002-09-29 || Hans Florine, Yuji Hirayama || 2:48:55<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supertopo.com/climbing/thread.php?topic_id=8089&tn=0&mr=0 |title=New Nose Speed Record - 2:48 :: SuperTopo Rock Climbing Discussion Topic |publisher=Supertopo.com |accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2001-11 || Dean Potter, [[Timmy O'Neill]] || 3:24:20\n|-\n| 2001-10 || Hans Florine, [[Jim Herson]] || 3:57:27\n|-\n| 2001-10 || Dean Potter, Timmy O'Neill || 3:59:35<ref>Taking It Back, Gregory Crouch, [[Rock & Ice]], No 121, January 15, 2003</ref>\n|-\n| 1992 || Hans Florine, [[Peter Croft (climber)|Peter Croft]] || 4:22\n|-\n| 1991 || Peter Croft, [[Dave Schultz (climber)|Dave Schultz]] || 4:48\n|-\n| 1991 || Hans Florine, [[Andres Puhvel]] || 6:01\n|-\n| 1990 || Peter Croft, Dave Schultz || 6:40\n|-\n| 1990 || Hans Florine, [[Steve Schneider (climber)|Steve Schneider]] || 8:06\n|-\n| 1986 || [[John Bachar]], Peter Croft || 10:05<ref name=\"speedclimb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.speedclimb.com/yosemite/thenose.htm#98 |title=thenose |publisher=Speedclimb.com |accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1984 || [[Duncan Critchley]], [[Romain Vogler]] || 09:30 (approximate)<ref name=\"speedclimb\" />\n|-\n| 1975 || [[Jim Bridwell]], [[John Long (climber)|John Long]], [[Billy Westbay]] || 17:45\n|}\n\nA full list of records can be viewed online.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.speedclimb.com/yosemite/Elcap.htm |title=El Capitan speed ascents! |publisher=Speedclimb.com |accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref>\n\n==Significant features==\n[[File:Great Roof El Capitan.JPG|300px|thumb|''Great Roof'' as seen from the standard belay stance. With a climber at the end of the lens flare.]]\n\nThe pitch number below is approximate since there are alternative belay stations and the possibility of linking some pitches.\n\n===The Stovelegs===\n''The Stovelegs'', pitches 8 and 9, is an off-width crack which was originally protected by using pitons made from metal legs of wood burning stoves<ref>http://www.yosemiteclimbing.org/nose-gear</ref>.\n\n===King Swing===\nThe ''King Swing'' is part of pitch 17 and involves a rather large, swinging traverse (aka pendulum).\n\n===The Great Roof===\nThe ''Great Roof'' located on pitch 22, rated A1 or 5.13c, was expected to be the technical crux of free climbing the route, but was superseded by ''Changing Corners''.\n\n===Changing Corners===\n''Changing Corners'' on pitch 27, rated 5.14a/b, is usually considered to be the technical crux when free climbing ''The Nose''.\n\n==See also==\n*''[[El Capitan (film)|El Capitan]]''\n*[[List of noses]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* Climbing beta from [http://www.supertopo.com/rock-climbing/Yosemite-Valley-El-Capitan-The-Nose Supertopo], [http://www.mountainproject.com/v/the-nose/105924807 Mountain Project], [http://ghiz.org/nose.shtml Scott Ghiz], [https://books.google.com/books?id=ceyNAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA80 Putnam/Sloan], [http://www.bigwall.com/noseday.pdf Bigwall], [http://www.fishproducts.com/topos/yostopos/nose.html Fish Topos]\n* [http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2011/05/yosemite-climbing/interactive-graphic Interactive graphic] from [[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]\n* [http://www.elcapreport.com/ Elcap Report]\n* Gigapixel images from [http://www.yosemite-17-gigapixels.com/ Gerard Maynard], [http://www.xrez.com/yose_proj/yose_deepzoom/index.html XRes]\n{{Yosemite National Park}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nose (El Capitan), The}}\n[[Category:Climbing routes]]\n[[Category:Yosemite National Park]]\n", "name_user": "Dmoore5556", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:correct page links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Nose_(El_Capitan)"}
{"title_page": "Yavnella", "text_new": "{{short description|Genus of ants}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Taxobox\n|name = ''Yavnella''\n|image = Yavnella argamani casent0101728 profile 1.jpg\n|image_caption=''[[Yavnella argamani]]'' male\n|regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n|phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n|classis = [[Insect]]a\n|ordo = [[Hymenoptera]]\n|familia = [[Formicidae]]\n|subfamilia = [[Leptanillinae]]\n|tribus = [[Leptanillini]]\n|genus = '''''Yavnella'''''\n|genus_authority = Kugler, 1987\n|type_species = ''Yavnella argamani''\n|type_species_authority = Kugler, 1987\n|diversity_link = #Species\n|diversity = 2 species\n|diversity_ref = <ref name=\"AntCat\">{{AntCat|430172|''Yavnella''|2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Yavnella''''' is a [[genus]] of [[ant]]s in the [[subfamily]] [[Leptanillinae]].<ref name=\"AWYavnella\"/> Its two species are distributed in [[India]] and [[Israel]].<ref name=\"Kugler_1987\"/> The genus is known only from male specimens.<ref name=\"Ogata_et_al_1995\"/>\n\n==Species==\n* ''[[Yavnella argamani]]'' <small>Kugler, 1987</small>&nbsp;\u2013 Israel\n* ''[[Yavnella indica]]'' <small>Kugler, 1987</small>&nbsp;\u2013 India\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"AWYavnella\">{{cite web |url=http://www.antweb.org/description.do?name=Yavnella&rank=genus&project=allantwebants |title= Genus: ''Yavnella''|date= |website=antweb.org |publisher=[[AntWeb]] |accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kugler_1987\">{{cite journal|last=Kugler|first= J.|date= 1987 |origyear=1986|title=The Leptanillinae (Hymenoptera: Formicidae) of Israel and a description of a new species from India. |journal=Israel Journal of Entomology |volume=20|pages=45\u201357}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Ogata_et_al_1995\">{{citation |last1=Ogata |first1=K. |last2=Terayama |first2=M. |last3=Masuko |first3=K. | year=1995 |title=The ant genus Leptanilla: discovery of the worker-associated male of ''L. japonica'', and a description of a new species from Taiwan (Hymenoptera: Formicidae: Leptanillinae). |journal=[[Systematic Entomology]] |volume=20 |pages=27\u201334 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-3113.1995.tb00081.x}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Yavnella|''Yavnella''}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q9383394}}\n\n[[Category:Leptanillinae]]\n[[Category:Ant genera]]\n[[Category:Hymenoptera of Asia]]\n\n\n{{ant-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Genus of ants}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Taxobox\n|name = ''Yavnella''\n|image = Yavnella argamani casent0101728 profile 1.jpg\n|image_caption=''[[Yavnella argamani]]'' male\n|regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n|phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n|classis = [[Insect]]a\n|ordo = [[Hymenoptera]]\n|familia = [[Formicidae]]\n|subfamilia = [[Leptanillinae]]\n|tribus = [[Leptanillini]]\n|genus = '''''Yavnella'''''\n|genus_authority = Kugler, 1987\n|type_species = ''Yavnella argamani''\n|type_species_authority = Kugler, 1987\n|diversity_link = #Species\n|diversity = 2 species\n|diversity_ref = <ref name=\"AntCat\">{{AntCat|430172|''Yavnella''|2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Yavnella''''' is a [[genus]] of [[ant]]s in the [[subfamily]] [[Leptanillinae]].<ref name=\"AWYavnella\"/> Its two species are distributed in [[India]] and [[Israel]].<ref name=\"Kugler_1987\"/> The genus is known only from males.<ref name=\"Ogata_et_al_1995\"/>\n\n==Species==\n* ''[[Yavnella argamani]]'' <small>Kugler, 1987</small>&nbsp;\u2013 Israel\n* ''[[Yavnella indica]]'' <small>Kugler, 1987</small>&nbsp;\u2013 India\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"AWYavnella\">{{cite web |url=http://www.antweb.org/description.do?name=Yavnella&rank=genus&project=allantwebants |title= Genus: ''Yavnella''|date= |website=antweb.org |publisher=[[AntWeb]] |accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kugler_1987\">{{cite journal|last=Kugler|first= J.|date= 1987 |origyear=1986|title=The Leptanillinae (Hymenoptera: Formicidae) of Israel and a description of a new species from India. |journal=Israel Journal of Entomology |volume=20|pages=45\u201357}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Ogata_et_al_1995\">{{citation |last1=Ogata |first1=K. |last2=Terayama |first2=M. |last3=Masuko |first3=K. | year=1995 |title=The ant genus Leptanilla: discovery of the worker-associated male of ''L. japonica'', and a description of a new species from Taiwan (Hymenoptera: Formicidae: Leptanillinae). |journal=[[Systematic Entomology]] |volume=20 |pages=27\u201334 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-3113.1995.tb00081.x}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|Yavnella|''Yavnella''}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q9383394}}\n\n[[Category:Leptanillinae]]\n[[Category:Ant genera]]\n[[Category:Hymenoptera of Asia]]\n\n\n{{ant-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Vagabond nanoda", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copyedit.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yavnella"}
{"title_page": "Kate Dickie", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kate Dickie\n| image              = Kate Dickie by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption            = Dickie in 2017\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1971|3|23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[East Kilbride]], Scotland\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| alma_mater         = [[Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama]]\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 1994\u2013present\n| children           = 1\n}}\n\n'''Kate Dickie''' (born 23 March 1971) is a Scottish actress who has appeared in television series, [[stage plays]] and films. She is known for her television roles as Lex in the [[BBC]] series ''[[Tinsel Town]]'' (2000\u20132001) and [[Lysa_Arryn#Lysa_Arryn|Lysa Arryn]] in the [[HBO]] series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' (2011, 2014). She supports the theatre company Solar Bear, which is known for its collaborations with deaf people, in part through her role as a patron.<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20070603/ai_n19202004 Celebrated at Cannes, but work still not easy for Kate THEATRE: | Sunday Herald, The | Find Articles at BNET<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nDickie is also known for her portrayal of the security operative Jackie in her 2006 feature-film debut ''[[Red Road (film)|Red Road]]'', directed by [[Andrea Arnold]], for which she won several awards, including Best Actress at the [[British Academy Scotland Awards]] and the [[BIFA Award for Best Performance by an Actress in a British Independent Film|British Independent Film Award for Best Actress]]. She again won Best Actress at the [[2016 British Academy Scotland Awards]] for the film ''[[Couple in a Hole]]''. Her other film appearances include ''[[Prometheus (2012 film)|Prometheus]]'' (2012), ''[[Filth (film)|Filth]]'' (2013), ''[[The Witch (2015 film)|The Witch]]'' (2015) and ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]'' (2017).\n\n== Early life ==\nDickie was born in [[East Kilbride]], Scotland, but spent part of her childhood in different parts of Scotland, [[Wigtownshire]], [[Dumfries and Galloway|Galloway]], [[Perthshire]] and [[Ayrshire]], due to frequent moves by her family. From an early age she discovered her passion for acting, which her parents also supported. Coming from a working-class family (her father was a farmer and gardener) in which no family member had been in the arts before, she was embarrassed to call herself an actress since she was afraid to be called pretentious.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20070603/ai_n19201992 Waiting in the wings Kate Dickie wasn't prepared for the fame that | Sunday Herald, The | Find Articles at BNET<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318051008/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20070603/ai_n19201992 |date=18 March 2009 }}</ref> Her desire for drama classes supported her to overcome her insecurities that appeared through the frequent school changes and helped her dealing with adjusting to new people and surroundings. After leaving school she went to [[Adam Smith College|college in Kirkcaldy]] to study for a national certificate in drama. In 1990, she won a place at the [[Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama]] and decided to stay in Glasgow.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Dickie started to work in theatre and had the opportunity to perform with some of Scotland's best companies. She finally achieved her breakthrough in 2000, in the BBC Scotland / Raindog series, ''Tinsel Town''.<ref name=autogenerated1/>\n\n== Acting career ==\nThrough Dickie's performance in her film debut ''[[Red Road (film)|Red Road]]'' (in which she plays a security camera operative who gets involved with people's everyday lives through her camera perspective and who begins to stalk a man for reasons relating to her past) with her former drama school mate and co-star [[Tony Curran]], she gained more recognition as a serious actress.<ref>[http://www.viewlondon.co.uk/films/red-road-film-review-17286.html Red Road \u2013 Movie Review<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.monstersandcritics.com/movies/reviews/article_1289234.php/Movie_Review_Red_Road Movie Review: Red Road<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520043448/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/movies/reviews/article_1289234.php/Movie_Review_Red_Road |date=20 May 2011 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2006/10/25/red_road_2006_review.shtml BBC \u2013 Movies \u2013 review \u2013 Red Road<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/film-and-tv/features/the-brit-pack-of-uk-cinema-445773.html The Brit pack of UK cinema \u2013 Features, Film & TV \u2013 The Independent<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn the stage play ''[[Aalst (play)|Aalst]]'', based on the true story of a couple who had killed their children and were sentenced in a high-profile trial, Dickie plays one of the parents. Her motivation to perform this role was her feeling of \"responsibility to play people like that and to give them a voice. People that are not necessarily good or nice and have good lives.\"<ref name=autogenerated1/>\n\nDickie reprised the role of Jackie in ''[[Donkeys (film)|Donkeys]]'', a follow-up to ''Red Road'' which is directed by Morag McKinnon. She portrayed Mary in the United Kingdom [[supernatural]] [[thriller film]] ''[[Outcast (2010 film)|Outcast]]''.<ref>[http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18088 AFM '09: First Image, Details on Thriller 'Outcast']</ref>\n\nDickie was a swimming trainer in the 2010 television film ''[[Dive (TV series)|Dive]]''.\n\nShe appears in the [[HBO]] television series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', where she plays the role of [[Lysa Arryn]].<ref>[http://thestir.cafemom.com/entertainment/157643/game_of_thrones_season_4.html The Sir Cafe Mom] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140430014634/http://thestir.cafemom.com/entertainment/157643/game_of_thrones_season_4.html |date=30 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Dickie appeared in season 5 episode of Shetland.\n\n==Personal life==\nDickie lives with her daughter, Molly Christie (born in 2004), and her boyfriend, Kenny, in Glasgow.{{cn|date=December 2016}}\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role\n|-\n| 1994 || ''Bonjour Tristesse'' ||\n|-\n| 1997\u201398 || ''Timeless'' ||\n|-\n| 1999 || ''Electra'' || Electra\n|-\n| 1999 || ''Mainstream'' ||\n|-\n| 2000 || ''AD'' ||\n|-\n| 2001 || ''Blooded'' ||\n|-\n|2002\n|''Running Girl''\n|Running Girl\n|-\n| 2002\u201303 || ''Lament'' ||\n|-\n| 2003 || ''The Entertainer'' ||\n|-\n| 2005 || ''Boiling a Frog'' || Fooaltiyeman\n|-\n| 2005 || ''Trojan Woman'' || Andromache\n|-\n| 2007 || ''Aalst'' || Cathy Delany\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Note\n|-\n| 1994 || ''[[Rab C. Nesbitt]]'' || Young girl || (1 episode) \u2013 \"Mother\"\n|-\n| 2000\u20132001 || ''[[Tinsel Town]]'' || Lex ||\n|-\n| 2003 || ''{{sortname|The|Vice|dab=TV series}}'' || Beverly || (1 episode) \u2013 \"Gameboys\"\n|-\n| 2003 || ''[[Taggart]]'' ||   || (1 episode) \u2013 \"Penthouse and Pavement\"\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Still Game]]'' || Pregnant Girl || (1 episode, Series 3) \u2013 \"Swottin\"\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Film '72]]'' || Herself ||\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Taggart]]'' || Wendy Nuget || (1 episode) \u2013 \"Island\"   (2003)\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[He Kills Coppers]]'' || Janis ||\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Five Daughters]]'' || Isabella Clennell || (2 episodes)\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Dive (TV series)|Dive]]'' || Alison || (2 episodes)\n|-\n| 2010 || ''{{sortname|The|Pillars of the Earth|dab=miniseries}}'' || Agnes Builder ||\n|-\n| 2011, <br> 2014 